  "prompt": "How do you find the molar mass of CuSO4?",
  "response": "To find the molar mass of copper(II) sulfate (CuSO\u2084), you need to sum the atomic masses of all the atoms in its chemical formula. Here\u2019s the step-by-step process:\n\n1. **Identify the elements and their quantities in CuSO\u2084:**\n   - Copper (Cu): 1 atom\n   - Sulfur (S): 1 atom\n   - Oxygen (O): 4 atoms\n\n2. **Look up the atomic masses of each element (from the periodic table):**\n   - The atomic mass of Cu is approximately **63.55 g/mol**.\n   - The atomic mass of S is approximately **32.07 g/mol**.\n   - The atomic mass of O is approximately **16.00 g/mol**.\n\n3. **Calculate the total mass of each element:**\n   - Mass of Cu = \\( 1 \\times 63.55 = 63.55 \\) g/mol\n   - Mass of S = \\( 1 \\times 32.07 = 32.07 \\) g/mol\n   - Mass of O = \\( 4 \\times 16.00 = 64.00 \\) g/mol\n\n4. **Add the masses together to find the molar mass of CuSO\u2084:**\n   \\[\n   \\text{Molar mass of CuSO\u2084} = 63.55 + 32.07 + 64.00 = 159.62 \\, \\text{g/mol}\n   \\]\n\nSo, the molar mass of CuSO\u2084 is approximately **159.62 g/mol**.",
